UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 the appointment of a committee to receive evidence and take testimony at such times and
2 places as set forth in this Resolution and make a finding of whether the accused shall be
3 convicted or acquitted of the charges found in the Articles of Impeachment. The
4 President of the Senate shall appoint a chairman of the committee. The committee shall
5 exercise all the powers and functions conferred upon it by the Senate and President of the
6 Senate under the impeachment Rules of Procedure as set forth in this Resolution and
7 approved by the Senate when sitting as a Court of Impeachment. Unless otherwise
8 ordered by the Senate, the committee shall follow these impeachment Rules of Procedure
9 of the Senate when sitting as a Court of Impeachment.
10 Section 3. The Clerk of the Senate shall inform the House of Representatives
11 and the committee thereof appointed to prosecute the impeachment that the Senate has
12 resolved itself into a Court of Impeachment, that the Clerk shall summon the Respondent
13 by precept to appear on that day and hour for the hearing, and that the Clerk shall, at the
14 instance of the committee chair and at the instance of the accused, issue process for the
15 summoning of witnesses and the production of such books, papers, documents, or
16 tangible things as may be desired by the committee or the Respondent. If the House has
17 previously communicated with the Respondent, service of the summons by email and
18 certified mail shall be deemed sufficient.
19 Section 4. Following the hearing and pursuant to Senate Rule 39A, the
20 appointed Senate committee shall present a written report of its findings to the full
21 Senate, which shall include the recording of the proceedings, evidence received and
22 testimony presented to the committee, and findings of whether the accused shall be
23 convicted or acquitted of the charges in the Articles of Impeachment. That report shall be
24 received by the Senate, and the evidence received and the testimony taken shall be
25 considered as having been received and taken before the Senate, and subject to the right
26 of the Senate to determine competency, relevancy, and materiality. Nothing herein shall
27 prevent the Senate from sending for any witness and hearing his or her testimony in the
Page 2 of 10
