1 open Senate, or by order of the Senate having the entire trial in the open Senate.
2 Section 5. For the purpose of the governing the procedures at the impeachment
3 hearing, there are hereby adopted by the Senate the following rules:
4 RULES GOVERNING THE SENATE OF THE
5 COMMONWEALTH OF KENTUCKY
6 SITTING AS A COURT OF IMPEACHMENT
7 (1) Rules of Procedure
8 Except as otherwise provided, and when not in conflict with these Rules, the
9 Standing Rules of the Senate shall apply, and the presiding officer shall retain the
10 authority to invoke the Rules of the Senate.
11 (2) Rules of Evidence
12 When not in conflict with these Rules or the Rules of the Senate, the rules of
13 evidence used in courts of general jurisdiction in the Commonwealth shall serve as a
14 guide. However, variation from the rules of evidence may be permitted, and reliable
15 evidence admitted, subject to the same being determined relevant, whenever the interests
16 of justice require.
17 (3) Floor Privileges
18 Senators; members of the House Committee and its counsel and staff; personnel of
19 the Court of Impeachment; the Presiding Officer and counsel; the Respondent and
20 counsel; and those with proper identification as issued by the Clerk of the Court of
21 Impeachment shall be permitted within the Senate Chambers during the trial.
22 (4) Marshal of the Court of Impeachment
23 The Court of Impeachment shall appoint a Marshal, who shall be the Sergeant at
24 Arms of the Senate, and an Assistant Marshal.
25 (5) Clerk of the Court of Impeachment
26 The Clerk of the Senate shall serve and be referred to as the Clerk of the Court of
27 Impeachment and shall administer the oath to all witnesses, keep the Journal of the
Page 3 of 10
XXXX 3/25/2026 5:33 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 Senate sitting as a Court of Impeachment, and perform all other duties usually performed
2 by a clerk of a court of record in this Commonwealth. An Assistant Clerk may also be
3 appointed.
4 (6) Presiding Officer
5 When the Senate sits as a Court of Impeachment, the President of the Senate shall
6 preside, unless another Presiding Officer is appointed.
7 (7) Eligibility of Senators
8 Each Senator shall, by virtue of his or her office, be eligible to participate in the
9 impeachment proceedings, and no senator shall be subject to disqualification except as
10 provided in Rule 8.
11 (8) Attendance
12 No member of the whole Senate or the committee appointed pursuant to Senate
13 Rule 39A, whichever is receiving evidence, shall cast a final vote on the Articles of
14 Impeachment on which the member has not heard a substantial portion of the testimony
15 and evidence or reviewed the video tapes of those portions of the testimony and evidence
16 which the member did not hear. Members of the Senate shall be present to vote on the
17 final report of the committee appointed pursuant to Senate Rule 39A.
18 (9) General Powers
19 The Senate shall have the power to compel the attendance of witnesses, to enforce
20 obedience to its orders, precepts, summons, and judgments; to preserve order; to punish
21 in the manner prescribed by law contempt of or disobedience of its orders, precepts,
22 summons, or judgments; and to make all lawful orders and rules as it may deem
23 necessary for the performance of its duties as a Court of Impeachment.
24 (10) Immunity
25 The parties, which include the House Committee and respondent, shall not call
26 Senators, members of the House Committee, its counsel and staff, the Presiding Officer,
27 counsel, or staff of the Court of Impeachment or Legislative Research Commission as
Page 4 of 10
XXXX 3/25/2026 5:33 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 witnesses, and shall not subpoena their personal records or work papers.
2 (11) Representation
3 The House of Representatives shall be represented by an appointed Committee and
4 its counsel and staff. The Respondent shall appear in person or by counsel.
5 (12) Pretrial Conference
6 Counsel for the parties may meet with the Presiding Officer on his or her order or
7 on motion by any party, at a time set by the Presiding Officer, to rule on preliminary
8 motions, stipulate to facts and exhibits, and address issues that will expedite trial.
9 (13) Communications From Respondent
10 There shall be no communication, either directly or indirectly, from the Respondent
11 to any Senator unless it is submitted, in writing, by counsel for the Respondent, directly
12 to the Clerk of the Court of Impeachment. Communications shall be restricted to
13 information which would be admissible in a court of law. The Presiding Officer shall rule
14 on the admissibility of the communication.
15 (14) Communications From Individuals
16 At the time the Senate resolves itself into a Court of Impeachment, no individual,
17 except another Senator, shall communicate any information relating to the impeachment
18 to a Senator within the Senate Chambers. Senators shall immediately report any
19 communication prohibited by this Rule to the Presiding Officer. Violation of this Rule
20 may be subject to punishment as provided in Rule 9 and Rule 27.
21 (15) Appearance
22 (a) The Senate shall appoint a day for hearing the impeachment. The Respondent
23 shall be summoned by precept, issued by the Clerk of the Court of Impeachment, to
24 appear on that day. The precept shall be served in person along with a copy of the
25 Articles of Impeachment and a copy of the Senate Resolution adopting these Rules by the
26 Marshal of the Court of Impeachment, the Assistant Marshal, or an officer of the
27 Kentucky State Police. Return of service shall be noted on the precept.
Page 5 of 10
XXXX 3/25/2026 5:33 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 (b) The precept shall be issued at least seven days before the day appointed for
2 trial.
3 (16) Subpoenas
4 (a) Subpoenas shall be issued by the Clerk of the Court of Impeachment for the
5 summoning of witnesses and the production of books, papers, documents, or tangible
6 things, on written application of the parties of their counsel. The Clerk may issue
7 Subpoenas in blank. A Senator may request a subpoena through the Clerk, which shall
8 issue if either party concurs. If neither party concurs with the request, a subpoena shall be
9 issued on a motion by the Senator, a second to the motion, and a vote of a majority of the
10 Senators present. The Senator may explain the reasons for his or her request and the vote
11 shall be taken without debate. All requests for subpoenas shall be made and issued at
12 least three days before the witness is scheduled to testify or produce books, papers,
13 documents, or tangible things at the hearing.
14 (b) Service of process for subpoenas shall be by personal service executed by
15 officers appointed by the Court of Impeachment or other officers authorized by law to
16 serve process in the Courts of Justice of the Commonwealth. Return of service shall be
17 noted on the subpoena.
18 (c) Upon disobedience to any process, the Senate may order the Clerk of the
19 Court of Impeachment to issue process for arresting the witness and seizing the books,
20 papers, documents, or tangible things which have been subpoenaed. Disobedience may be
21 punished in the manner provided for other witnesses before the General Assembly.
22 (d) A witness shall receive the same compensation, and have the same privileges
23 in going, remaining, and returning, as a witness in Circuit Court.
24 (17) Initial Appearance by Respondent
25 On the day appointed for the trial of the impeachment, the legislative business of
26 the Senate will be suspended, except as otherwise ordered by the Senate. At the time
27 fixed in the precept for the appearance of the Respondent and on proof of service, the
Page 6 of 10
XXXX 3/25/2026 5:33 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 Respondent shall be called to appear and answer the Articles of Impeachment. If she
2 appears or counsel on her behalf, the appearance shall be recorded. If she does not appear
3 either personally or by counsel, the same shall be recorded and the impeachment
4 proceedings conducted as though she were present and had entered a plea of not guilty.
5 (18) Answer
6 The Respondent shall answer, in writing, the Articles of Impeachment prior to the
7 opening of the trial of the impeachment. The answer shall be filed with the Clerk of the
8 Court of Impeachment.
9 (19) Order of Proof
10 After preliminary motions are heard and decided, the House Committee or its
11 counsel may make an opening statement not to exceed thirty minutes. The Respondent or
12 her counsel may then make an opening statement not to exceed thirty minutes. The
13 Presiding Officer shall determine the order of the presentation of evidence. Closing
14 arguments shall follow the presentation of all evidence to the Court of Impeachment and
15 shall not exceed one hour. On motion of either party before closing argument, the time
16 for closing argument may be extended by a vote of a majority of the Senators present.
17 The argument shall be opened and closed by or on behalf of the House Committee.
18 The Senate shall hear all evidence related to the Articles of Impeachment before
19 casting the final vote on the Articles of Impeachment.
20 (20) Oaths
21 (a) The following oath or affirmation shall be administered to each Senator and
22 the Presiding Officer by the Chief Justice of the Commonwealth or an Associate Justice:
23 "I do solemnly swear or affirm that I will faithfully and impartially try the
24 impeachment against Julie Muth Goodman, Circuit Judge, and give my decision
25 according to the law and the evidence."
26 (b) Before any witness shall give his or her testimony, the Clerk of the Court of
27 Impeachment shall administer to the witness the following oath or affirmation:
Page 7 of 10
XXXX 3/25/2026 5:33 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 "Do you solemnly swear or affirm that the testimony you shall give in the matter of
2 the impeachment of Julie Muth Goodman, Circuit Judge, shall be the truth, the whole
3 truth, and nothing but the truth, so help you God?"
4 (21) Witnesses
5 All witnesses shall be examined by the party producing them or its counsel, and
6 then cross-examined by the opposite party or its counsel. Only one attorney for each
7 party may examine each witness. The Presiding Officer may permit re-direct examination
8 and may permit re-cross examination. After completion of questioning by counsel, any
9 Senator desiring to question the witness shall be permitted to do so. If objection to a
10 Senator’s question is raised by counsel for either party or by a Senator, the Senator
11 desiring to question the witness may request a vote on the objection by a majority of the
12 Senators present.
13 (22) Motions
14 (a) The Presiding Officer may rule on all objections, motions, pleas, and
15 procedural questions made by the parties or their counsel. The ruling of the Presiding
16 Officer shall be the judgment of the Senate unless any Senator requests the Presiding
17 Officer to submit the question to be decided by a vote of a majority of the Senators
18 present.
19 (b) On motion of any Senator and a vote of a majority of the Senators present, or
20 at the request of the Presiding officer, the party shall commit the motion, plea, or
21 procedural question to writing.
22 (c) Except as otherwise provided, arguments by parties or their counsel on
23 motions shall be permitted only with a vote of a majority of the Senators present and shall
24 not exceed fifteen minutes, unless further extended by a majority vote.
25 (d) Roll call votes may be requested by a Senator and shall be taken if five
26 additional Senators concur in the request by standing.
27 (23) Verdict, Judgment, and Costs
Page 8 of 10
XXXX 3/25/2026 5:33 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 (a) After closing arguments, all qualified Senators shall be required to vote on the
2 question of whether to sustain the Articles of Impeachment. A vote to sustain the Articles
3 shall be based on clear and convincing evidence that the Articles are true and that the
4 Articles constitute impeachable offenses. The vote on whether to sustain shall be taken as
5 a roll call vote.
6 (b) If the Respondent is acquitted on the Articles of Impeachment, a judgment of
7 acquittal shall be pronounced and entered on the Journal on the Court of Impeachment.
8 (c) If two-thirds of the Senators present vote to sustain the Articles of
9 Impeachment, the Court of Impeachment shall, by resolution, pronounce judgment of
10 conviction and removal from office under the Constitution. The resolution shall be
11 entered upon the Journal of the Court of Impeachment.
12 (d) A copy of the judgment shall be filed in the Office of the Secretary of State.
13 (e) In an impeachment proceeding prosecuted before the Senate, if the
14 Respondent is acquitted, the Commonwealth shall pay the costs of the Respondent. If the
15 Respondent is found guilty, she shall pay the Commonwealth the costs incurred in behalf
16 of the prosecution. Costs shall be taxed by the Clerk of the Court of Impeachment. In no
17 event shall costs include attorney's fees incurred by the Commonwealth or the
18 Respondent.
19 (24) Official Record
20 The transcript of the proceedings of the Senate sitting as a Court of Impeachment
21 shall be the recordings produced by Kentucky Educational Television/Legislative
22 Research Commission YouTube Channel.
23 (25) Instruction
24 At any time, on his or her own motion or on request of a Senator, the Presiding
25 Officer may instruct the Senators on procedural matters.
26 (26) Conferences
27 At any point during the proceedings and on the request of any Senator, there shall
Page 9 of 10
XXXX 3/25/2026 5:33 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2590
1 be an immediate conference of all the Senators present. Conferences provided for under
2 this Rule may be closed on a vote of a majority of the Senators present.
3 (27) Prohibited Conduct
4 Threats against or interference with the Court of Impeachment may be prosecuted
5 as provided by law.
6 (28) Amendments to Rules
7 These Rules may be suspended or amended by a vote of two-thirds of the Senators
8 present.
